---
/** Personal finance: gender pay gap. */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import GenderPayGapCalculator from '../../components/calculators/GenderPayGapCalculator.tsx';
import { genderPayGap } from '../../lib/personal-finance';
import { OCCUPATIONS } from '../../data/occupations-pay';
import { formatMoney, formatPct } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const phys = OCCUPATIONS.find((o) => o.name.startsWith('Physician'))!;
const ex = genderPayGap(phys, 208000, 'female', 25, 0.07);
---

<Base
  title="Gender pay gap calculator 2026"
  description="See the male/female median pay gap in your occupation, where your salary sits, and the lifetime cost of the gap — compounded over a career if invested."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Personal finance</p>
    <h1>Gender pay gap calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The gap is usually quoted as a single percentage. This shows it in dollars for your occupation — and what it compounds to over a career.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    The pay gap is easy to wave away as a statistic. In dollars, over a career, it isn't. This shows the male/female
    median gap for your occupation, where your own salary falls against the relevant median, and — the part that
    lands hardest — what that annual gap grows to if the difference had been invested over your remaining career.
  </p>

  <GenderPayGapCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>Physicians and surgeons — one of the widest gaps of any occupation — for a woman earning the female median, 25 years left:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Measure</th><th>Value</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Median gap (men vs women)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.occupationGap)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Women earn less by</td><td>{formatPct(ex.occupationGapPct)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lifetime cost of the gap (plain sum)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.lifetimeGapSimple)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lifetime cost if invested (at 7%)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.lifetimeGapInvested)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    A {formatMoney(ex.occupationGap)} annual gap — {formatPct(ex.occupationGapPct)} — is {formatMoney(ex.lifetimeGapSimple)}
    {' '}across 25 years in plain dollars, and {formatMoney(ex.lifetimeGapInvested)} if that difference had been
    invested. The compounding is the real story: an annual gap becomes a retirement-sized number.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Where do the occupation figures come from?</h3>
    <p>They're reference medians for each occupation in the style of Bureau of Labor Statistics data — illustrative,
      not a live feed. They describe typical pay for the field, not your pay, which you enter yourself.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does the gap mean equal work is paid unequally?</h3>
    <p>Part of a raw gap reflects differences in role, specialty, hours and time out of the workforce; part remains
      after those are accounted for. This shows the raw median difference — the starting point, not the whole
      explanation.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What can I do with this?</h3>
    <p>Use it as leverage: knowing the median for your occupation and where you sit is the groundwork for a
      negotiation. The lifetime figure is why closing even a small gap early is worth the harder conversation now.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/raise-calculator/">Raise calculator</a> — is an offer a real raise?</li>
    <li><a href="/salary-by-city-calculator/">Salary by city</a> — pay in context of cost of living</li>
    <li><a href="/net-worth-calculator/">Net worth</a> — where the compounding lands</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">Occupation medians are approximate reference data, not a statement about individual pay. Not financial advice.</p>
</Base>
